 in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Longland","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: locative name from any of the many minor places in England called Longland(s) or Langland(s). There has probably been some confusion with the Scottish surname   Langlands  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Langland","meanings":["English: topographic name from Old English <i>lang</i>, <i>long</i> ‘long’ + <i>land</i> ‘land’, ‘territory’.","Scottish: habitational name from Langlands in Guthrie (Angus).","Norwegian: variant of   Langeland  ."]},{"name":"Langlands","meanings":["Scottish: habitational name from Langlands in Guthrie (Angus)."]},{"name":"Longlands","meanings":["English, Scottish: variant of   Longland   with plural or post-medieval excrescent  <i>-s</i>. There has probably been some confusion with the Scottish surname   Langlands  ."]}]},{"name":"Margaret","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."],"variants":[{"name":"Margareta","meanings":["From the Latin form of Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>.  See  <b>Margaret</b>   ."]},{"name":"Margaretta","meanings":["An extremely common given name from the Middle Ages onwards, derived via Old French <i>Marguerite</i> and Latin <i>Margarita</i> from Greek <i>Margarītēs</i>, from <i>margaron</i> ‘pearl’, a word ultimately of Hebrew origin. The name was always understood to mean ‘pearl’ throughout the Middle Ages. The first  St Margaret  was martyred at Antioch in Pisidia during the persecution instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  in the early 4th century. However, there is some doubt about her name, as the same saint is venerated in the Orthodox Church as   Marina .  There were several other saintly bearers of the name, including St Margaret of Scotland (  d. 1093 ), wife of  King Malcolm Canmore  and daughter of Edmund Ironside of England. It was also the name of the wife of  Henry VI  of England,  Margaret of Anjou  (  1430–82 ), and of  Margaret Tudor  (  1489–1541 ), sister of  Henry VIII , who married James IV of Scotland and ruled as regent there after his death.  See also  Margery  ,   Marjorie ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Margaret de Longland was born about 1362, in England, United Kingdom, her father, John de Longland, was 41 and her mother, Isabel Beaupré, was 24. She had at least 1 daughter with John Deviock. She died about 1380, in her hometown, at the age of 20, and was buried in Bridgwater, Somerset, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"Abt 1362–Abt 1380":"umbes 1362–umbes 1380","1353–1421":"1353–1421","1362–1380":"1362–1380","1370–1419":"1370–1419","1355–1380":"1355–1380","1352–1413":"1352–1413","1378–1448":"1378–1448","1380–1421":"1380–1421","1323–1380":"1323–1380","1339–1380":"1339–1380","about 1380":"umbe